olnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graunte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","North German: probably a variant of <b>Grönke</b> (see   Groenke  ) and   Greunke  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Groenke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Hans, Klaus, Kurt.","North German (<b>Grönke</b>): diminutive of <b>Grön</b> (see   Groen   and   Gruen  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mark","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name   Marcus  , borne by the Evangelist, author of the second gospel in the New Testament, and by several other early and medieval saints. In Arthurian legend,  King Mark  is the aged ruler of Cornwall to whom Isolde is brought as a bride by Tristan; his name was presumably of Celtic origin, perhaps derived from the element <i>march</i> ‘horse’. This was not a particularly common name in the Middle Ages but was in more frequent use by the end of the 16th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":52,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":61,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":72,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Mark Graunte was born in 1497, in Quadring, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Robert Grantte, was 36 and his mother, Isolel Ross, was 34. He married Alyce Grante. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1569, in his hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1497–1569":"1497–1569","1508–1579":"1508–1579","1518–1567":"1518–1567","1461–1569":"1461–1569","1463–1530":"1463–1530","1461":"1461","11 Jan 1567":"11. jaanuar 1567","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1579":"1579","1567":"1567","ABT 1483":"1483","1497":"1497","1530":"1530","1463":"1463","1508":"1508","1518":"1518","1549":"1549","W. Allington, Lincolnshire, England":"West Allington, Lincolnshire, England","Quadring, Lincolnshire, England":"Quadring, Lincolnshire, England","West Allington, Lincolnshire, England":"West Allington, Lincolnshire, England","Allington, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Allington, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1497–1569":"1497–1569","1508–1579":"1508–1579","1518–1567":"1518–1567","1461–1569":"1461–1569","1463–1530":"1463–1530","1461":"1461","11 Jan 1567":"11. tammikuuta 1567